05293nam a22008295i 9780231544177DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018060759  a97802315441777 a10.7312/chiu182442doi  a(DE-B1597)526867  a(OCoLC)1118692122  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aU22b.C5248 2019 7aPOL0110102bisacsh04a172/.422231 aChiu, Yvonne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConspiring with the Enemy :bThe Ethic of Cooperation in Warfare /cYvonne Chiu. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tI. The Horrors of War and the Nature of Cooperation -- tII. Cooperation for a Fair Fight -- tIII. Cooperation to Minimize Damage to Particular Classes of People -- tIV. Cooperation to End War Quickly -- tV. The Limits of Ethics of Cooperation in Warfare -- tVI. Cooperative Ethics, Just War Theory, and the Structure of Modern Warfare -- tVII. Abdication of Judgment, Noncooperative Fights, and the Meaning of War -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite the strong influence of just war theory in military law and practice, warfare is commonly considered devoid of morality. Yet even in the most horrific of human activities, there is frequent communication and cooperation between enemies. One remarkable example is the Christmas truce—unofficial ceasefires between German and English trenches in December 1914 in which soldiers even mingled in No Man’s Land.In Conspiring with the Enemy, Yvonne Chiu offers a new understanding of why and how enemies work together to constrain violence in warfare. Chiu argues that what she calls an ethic of cooperation is found in modern warfare to such an extent that it is often taken for granted. The importance of cooperation becomes especially clear when wartime ethics reach a gray area: To whom should the laws of war apply? Who qualifies as a combatant? Should guerrillas or terrorists receive protections? Fundamentally, Chiu shows, the norms of war rely on consensus on the existence and content of the laws of war. In a wide-ranging consideration of pivotal instances of cooperation, Chiu examines weapons bans, treatment of prisoners of war, and the Geneva Conventions, as well as the tensions between the ethic of cooperation and the pillars of just war theory. An original exploration of a crucial but overlooked phenomenon, Conspiring with the Enemy is a significant contribution to military ethics and political philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aConflict managementxInternational cooperation. 0aCooperationxHistory. 0aEnemies. 0aMilitary ethicsxHistory. 0aViolencexPreventionxInternational cooperation. 0aWar (International law)vCase studies. 0aWarxMoral and ethical aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2019z9783110606485oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/chiu1824440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231544177423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231544177.jpg  a978-3